    <h2>About</h2>
    <p>
      Dr. A.P.J. Abdul Kalam was a scientist, teacher, and the 11th President of India. He is remembered as the "Missile Man of India" for his great work in science and education.
    </p>

    <h2>Early Life</h2>
    <p>
      Born in 1931 in Rameswaram, Tamil Nadu, Kalam grew up in a humble family. He studied aerospace engineering and joined Indiaâ€™s top scientific organizations.
    </p>

    <h2>Life Timeline</h2>
    <div class="timeline">
      <div class="timeline-card"><strong>1931:</strong> Born in Rameswaram, Tamil Nadu.</div>
      <div class="timeline-card"><strong>1960:</strong> Joined DRDO as a scientist.</div>
      <div class="timeline-card"><strong>1969:</strong> Started working in ISRO and led the SLV-III project.</div>
      <div class="timeline-card"><strong>1980:</strong> Successfully launched satellite Rohini.</div>
      <div class="timeline-card"><strong>1998:</strong> Led Pokhran-II nuclear tests.</div>
      <div class="timeline-card"><strong>2002:</strong> Became the 11th President of India.</div>
      <div class="timeline-card"><strong>2015:</strong> Passed away while delivering a speech at IIM Shillong.</div>
    </div>

    <h2>Achievements</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Developed India's missile systems: Agni and Prithvi.</li>
      <li>Played key role in Pokhran-II nuclear tests.</li>
      <li>Honored with Bharat Ratna, Padma Bhushan, and Padma Vibhushan.</li>
      <li>Wrote inspiring books like <i>Wings of Fire</i>.</li>
      <li>Encouraged youth to dream big and work hard.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Famous Quote</h2>
    <blockquote>
      "Dream is not that which you see while sleeping, it is something that does not let you sleep."
    </blockquote>

